It all depends on what kind of story you want to tell. If you want a buddy adventure story, where two people cooperate to survive, and they need to communicate, handwave it and get to the adventure. I've only seen "they have to learn to communicate" used effectively once in an adventure story:

https://www.gutenberg.org/files/23731/23731-h/23731-h.htm

That's "A Martian Odyssey" by Stanley G. Weinbaum. A human and an alien meet and have to cooperate to survive. One of the plot points is that the human can't pick up much of anything of the alien's language, but the alien learns English pretty damn quick, because, and this is another important plot point, he is scary smart.

It's a relatively short story, but the author was pretty good by early 20th Century pulp "Men's Adventure" magazine standards and he made it work. I have seen others try it and the story always stops while the author goes down a rabbit hole filled with morphemes and syntax.

>>47114773
>I greatly appreciate the editorial work.
I'm glad. When I do it, some people appreciate it, but some people get incredibly angry about it. I do it anyway, since it's better to ask for forgiveness than permission.
I'll continue the editorial work for future chapters then. It slows down my reading, but not to an extent that stops me from enjoying it. As I said, I did enjoy chapter one!
>AP, Chicago, APA style
Honestly I don't know any of those, myself. My own style is very focused on my own intuition: me the individual, a native speaker of English. I feel that whatever is clear between normal people is correct, regardless of what English teachers think. This is probably because I had some of a background in linguistics years ago, and also because the English teachers I had in school honestly weren't good at grammar concepts.
>As for the gross misuse for commas, I could never figure out what's good or not and office keeps trying to shove semicolons in everywhere, so like a terminal illness in a man, I just ignore it.
Reasonable. I think an important way to find out how a sentence flows is to say it out loud. Not as if dictating it, but as if saying what you mean to another human right in front of you. Remember that English is primarily a spoken language, though it also happens to be written down.
If you assume all punctuation marks have different lengths of pausing between words, you'll end up finding the correct mark the vast majority of the time. A comma is a small pause, a period is a longer pause, and other marks are somewhere in between.

Aha, I see. The way I see it, think about how you say the possessive out loud for these words:
fox
rose
More likely than not, you say fox's or rose's out loud rather than fox' or rose'. So, why would you say boss' rather than boss's? English is based on sounds rather than letters, really.
As far as I know, every possessive sounds the same as the plural, though there is some chance I may be wrong on that, that there may be some edge case I'm not thinking of.

Heh! I grew up with single spaces, but after high school, I learnt about the existence of double-spacing and quickly switched to it. It's now my actual habit: I think it has advantages.
